'''Colonization resistance''' is the mechanism whereby the [[intestinal microbiota]] protects itself against incursion by new and often harmful [[microorganisms]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Wilson, Michael|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q9Qx9oRKO_kC&dq|title=Microbial inhabitants of humans: their ecology and role in health and disease|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2005|isbn=9780521841580}}</ref><ref>Trevor Lawley and Alan Walker, [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3533696/ "Intestinal colonization resistance"], ''[[Immunology (journal)|Immunology]]'', volume 38, pages 1-11, 2013.</ref>
Colonization resistance was first identified in 1967, and it was initially referred to as antibiotic associated susceptibility. It was observed that animals being treated with the antibiotic [[streptomycin]] were susceptible to ''[[Salmonella enterica]]'' at doses 10,000 fold lower than the standard minimal infectious dose.<ref>{{cite journal|authors=Bohnhoff M, Miller CP|url=http://jid.oxfordjournals.org/content/111/2/117.long|title=Enhanced Susceptibility to Salmonella Infection in Streptomycin-Treated Mice|journal=Journal of Infectious Diseases|volume=111|issue=2|pages=117–127|year=1962|doi=10.1093/infdis/111.2.117}}{{subscription required}}</ref> This led to investigations about the mechanisms utilized by endogenous microbial populations that conferred protection against exogenous pathogens attempting to colonize the [[gut flora]].
It has been observed that colonization resistance can occur within the host in a 'direct' or 'indirect' manner.<ref>{{cite journal|authors=Buffie CG, Pamer EG|title=Microbiota-mediated colonization resistance against intestinal pathogens|url=http://www.nature.com/nri/journal/v13/n11/pdf/nri3535.pdf|journal=Nature Reviews Immunology|year=2013|volume=13|pages=790–801|doi=10.1038/nri3535|pmc=4194195}}</ref> The former refers to particular components of the microbiota directly competing with exogenous pathogens for nutritional niches (e.g. ''Bacteroides thetaiotaomicron'' directly competes with ''[[Citrobacter rodentium]]'' for [[carbohydrates]] in the [[intestinal lumen]]<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/content/336/6086/1325.long|title=Regulated virulence controls the ability of a pathogen to compete with the gut microbiota|journal=Science|year=2012|volume=336|number=6086|pages=1325–1329|doi=10.1126/science.1222195|pmid=22582016|pmc=3439148|author=Kamada N, Kim YG, Sham HP, Vallance BA, Puente JL, Martens EC, Núñez G}}</ref>) or by producing growth inhibitors (e.g. ''Bacteroides thuringiensis'' can secrete [[bacteriocin]] that directly targets spore-forming ''[[Clostridium difficile (bacteria)|Clostridium difficile]]'', thus inhibiting its growth through an unknown mechanism),<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.pnas.org/content/107/20/9352.long|title=Thuricin CD, a posttranslationally modified bacteriocin with a narrow spectrum of activity against ''Clostridium difficile''|authors=Rea, MC, Sit CS, Clayton E, O'Connor PM, Whittal RM, Zheng J, Vederas JC, Ross RP, Hill C|doi=10.1073/pnas.0913554107|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=107|number=20|pages=9352–9357|pmid=20435915|pmc=2889069}}</ref> that directly inhibits the colonizing pathogen. Indirect colonization resistance is thought to be mediated through the induction of [[immune]] responses in the host that concomitantly inhibit the colonizing pathogen. An example of this has been observed with ''B. thetaiotaomicron'', which can induce the host to produce antimicrobial C-type lectins [[REG3G|REGIIIγ]] and [[REGIIIβ]], both anti-microbial peptides that target [[gram-positive]] bacteria.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/content/313/5790/1126.long|authors=Cash HL, Whitham CV, Behrendt CL, Hooper LV|title=Symbiotic bacteria direct expression of an intestinal bactericidal lectin|journal=Science|date=25 August 2006|volume=313|number=5790|pages=1126–1130|doi=10.1126/science.1127119|pmid=16931762|pmc=2716667}}</ref>
