[[File:Thorbjørn Egners lesebøker.jpg|thumb|''Ola-Ola Heia'', the first volume of ''Thorbjørn Egners lesebøker''.]]
'''''Thorbjørn Egners lesebøker''''' ({{lang-en|Thorbjorn Egner's Readers}}) were a series of sixteen [[Basal reader|readers]] for [[elementary school]] written by [[Norway|Norwegian]] author [[Thorbjørn Egner]]. Egner spent 25 years working on the series{{spaced ndash}}consisting of collected literature as well as his own stories and illustrations{{spaced ndash}}and they were published in the years 1950&ndash;1972.<ref name="NSF">{{cite web|url=http://www.skoleforum.com/stiler/saeroppgave/det.aspx?id=2929|title=Thorbjørn Egner|publisher=Norsk Skoleforum|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2008-11-24}}</ref> The books were intended for children aged 8&ndash;15, which at the time corresponded to grades 2nd&ndash;9th.<ref name="NSF"/> Among the recurring characters was the young boy Ola-Ola, who grew up on a farm on the Norwegian countryside, but later moved to the city and had to adapt to a new life. Other stories took place in far-away lands, reminiscent of the environment in Egner's celebrated ''[[People and Robbers of Cardemon Town]]''. There were also a selection of songs and poems in between the stories.

The books took over the role held for decades by the readers of [[Nordahl Rolfsen]] in the Norwegian educational system. Rolfsen's books were published in the years 1892&ndash;1895, and had been the standard works since, but starting in the 1950s, Egner's books took over this position. Egner himself considered the series to be the ''[[Masterpiece|magnum opus]]'' of his collected works. In 1972, however{{spaced ndash}}the year when the last book in the series was published{{spaced ndash}}the educational program of Norwegian [[primary school]]s was altered. The new scheme largely abandoned the use of basic readers in the [[curriculum]]. As a result, Egner's textbooks were rendered virtually obsolete as educational tools.<ref name="DP">{{cite web|url=http://www.dyreparken.no/kart-parkinfo/kardemomme_by/Thorbjorn-Egner/|title=Thorbjørn Egner-biografi|publisher=Dyreparken|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2008-11-24}}</ref> The books remain an important part of the Norwegian cultural heritage, being considered children's classics, and some of them have been reprinted more recently.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bokkilden.no/SamboWeb/produkt.do?produktId=115869|title=Ola-Ola Heia|publisher=BokKilden|language=Norwegian|accessdate=2008-11-24}}</ref>

